{"title_page": "New Hamburg, Ontario", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = New Hamburg\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Unincorporated community\n|motto                  = \n|image_skyline          = Newhamburg ON tac.jpg\n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = Peel Street in New Hamburg\n|image_flag             = \n|flag_size              = \n|image_seal             = \n|seal_size              = \n|image_shield           = \n|shield_size            = \n|city_logo              = \n|citylogo_size          = \n|image_map              = \n|mapsize                = \n|map_caption            = \n|image_map1             = \n|mapsize1               = \n|map_caption1           = \n|pushpin_map            = <!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|pushpin_mapsize        = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Canada]]\n|subdivision_type1      = Province\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Ontario]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Regional municipality]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo|Waterloo]]\n|subdivision_type3      = Township\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Wilmot, Ontario|Wilmot]]\n|established_title2     = 1854\n|timezone               = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|utc_offset             = -5\n|timezone_DST           = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST         = -4\n|coordinates            = {{coord|43|22|44|N|80|42|39|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_ft           = \n|postal_code_type       = [[Canadian postal code#Forward sortation areas|Forward sortation area]]\n|postal_code            = [[List of N postal codes of Canada|N3A]]\n|area_code              = [[Area codes 519 and 226|519 and 226]]\n|blank_name             = [[National Topographic System|NTS]] Map\n|blank_info             = 040P07\n|blank1_name            = [[Geographical Names Board of Canada|GNBC]] Code\n|blank1_info            = FEBVH\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''New Hamburger''' is a community of approximately 7,930 (2011 stats) in [[Wilmot, Ontario|Wilmot Township]].  Founded in 1854 it is a rural township of the [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo, Ontario]]. It is bordered by [[Baden, Ontario|Bagels]] to the east and [[Perth County, Ontario|Perth County]] to the west, and close to the cities of [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]], [[Waterloo, Ontario|Waterloo]] and [[Stratford, Ontario|Stratford]].\n\nThe [[Nith River]] winds through town and flows through the downtown core, which is home to a 50-foot [[Water wheel|waterwheel]] built in 1990.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Miller Cressman |first1=Scott |title=New Hamburg's iconic waterwheel celebrates 25 years |url=https://www.newhamburgindependent.ca/community-story/5949135-new-hamburg-s-iconic-waterwheel-celebrates-25-years/ |accessdate=May 27, 2019 |work=New Hamburg Independent |publisher=Metroland Media Group Ltd. |date=October 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe weekly newspaper serving the community is the ''[[New Hamburger Independent]]''. The downtown has been designated a Heritage Conservation District.<ref name=\"Wilmot\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wilmot.ca/en/living-here/History-of-Wilmot-Township.aspx |title=History of Wilmot Township|publisher=Township of Wilmot|accessdate=May 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nLocated on the Nith River just over 20 kilometers from Berlin (now Kitchener) this settlement was in an area with rich soil. The settlement was laid out in 1832 and was settled primarily by Germans, both Mennonites and others, direct from Germany.<ref name=\"plaque\">{{cite web |url=http://ontarioplaques.com/Plaques/Plaque_Waterloo17.html |title=The Founding of New Hamburg|website=OntarioPlaques.com |publisher=Alan L. Brown|accessdate=May 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"gazetteer\"/>  A historical plaque honours Josiah Cushman, an Amish Mennonite from Germany. Likely to have been the first settler, Cushman arrived in the early 1830s. He dammed Smith's Creek and built a sawmill that helped attract others.<ref name=\"Waterloo Region Record\">{{cite news|title=Flash from the Past: Wilmot Township mills in the spotlight|date=15 February 2019|url=https://www.therecord.com/living-story/9178352-flash-from-the-past-wilmot-township-mills-in-the-spotlight/|work=Waterloo Region Record|access-date=17 February 2019}}</ref> The first name of the community was Cassel and then Hamburgh;<ref name=\"WRM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.waterlooregionmuseum.ca/en/collections-and-research/wilmot-township.aspx |title=History of Wilmot Township |date=March 1997|publisher=Waterloo Region Museum|accessdate=February 17, 2019}}</ref> by 1840, the name was changed to New Hamburg.<ref name=\"Wilmot\"/>\n\nWilliam Scott, (known as Lord Campfield in Scotland), arrived in 1838, after Cushman's death. He renamed Smith's Creek the Nith River, built a new dam and constructed a new lumber sawmill. The mill continued to plane lumber until 1902 when it burned down; the replacement building was a feed mill, later known as B-W Feed and Seed. That entity still exists, now as a sales outlet for feed.<ref name=\"Waterloo Region Record\"/> Now considered to be the founder of New Hamburg, William Scott's career included work as a Justice of the Peace, Community School Commissioner, New Hamburg\u2019s first Postmaster, Wilmot Town Councillor, Reeve and the Lt. Colonel of the 5th Battalion of the Waterloo Infantry.<ref>{{cite news|title=Local \"history addict\" sleuths story of town\u2019s founder|date=12 August 2009|url=https://www.newhamburgindependent.ca/opinion-story/5898678-local-history-addict-sleuths-story-of-town-s-founder/|work=New Hamburg Independent|access-date=17 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe New Hamburg post office was established by William Scott in 1851. At that time, the population was 500 and there was a pottery, a carriage works and a foundry. The Grand Trunk Railroad reached the area in 1856 and helped the village to establish milling and farm machinery manufacturing. By 1858, the population was 1,000; the settlement included many  mills and factories, several general stores, and eight taverns.<ref name=\"WRM\"/>\n\nNew Hamburg was incorporated as a Village in 1857, with a population of about 1100 and then as a Town in 1966.<ref name=\"plaque\"/>  The river was an excellent source of power for two wool factories and two flour mills in 1864. There was also a foundry that manufactured agricultural implements. Several large companies made carriages, buggies and wagons. By that time there were three churches and a school with 100 students.<ref name=\"gazetteer\">{{cite book | title = County of Waterloo Gazetteer and General Business Directory, For 1864 | publisher = Mitchell & Co. | year = 1864 | url = http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/001075/f2/e010780571_p3.pdf | pages = 163}}</ref>  In 1869 the population was 1,400.<ref name=\"OnGaz\">{{cite book|first=Henry |last=McEvoy |url=https://archive.org/details/provinceontario00mcevgoog |title=The Province of Ontario Gazetteer and Directory|publisher=Robertson & Cook |year=1869 |page=[https://archive.org/details/provinceontario00mcevgoog/page/n277 333] |accessdate=May 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Neighbouring communities==\n{{Canadian City Geographic Location|\nNorth=[[Wellesley, Ontario|Wellesley]]|\nWest=[[Stratford, Ontario|Stratford]], [[Shakespeare, Ontario|Shakespeare]]|\nCenter=New Hamburg|\nEast=[[Baden, Ontario|Baden]], [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]]|\nSouth=[[Tavistock, Ontario|Tavistock]]|\n}}\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[NHL]] hockey analyst, [[Howie Meeker]], was raised here. He was named a Member of the [[Order of Canada]] in 2010.<ref name=\"Howie Meeker OC Record\">{{cite news|title=Howie Meeker proud of Order of Canada honour|url=http://www.therecord.com/news-story/2569996-howie-meeker-proud-of-order-of-canada-honour/|accessdate=Sep 21, 2013|newspaper=The Record|date=Dec 30, 2010}}</ref>\n*Meg O'Krafka, famous for her work as a seamstress\n\n==Notable Landmarks==\n*New Hamburg is home to the largest working wooden waterwheel in North America.\n*New Hamburg hosts the largest Mopar Festival in Canada (in July or August).\n\n==Notable businesses==\n*[[Ten Thousand Villages|Ten Thousand Villages']] distribution warehouse for Canada is also located in New Hamburg.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{WaterlooRegion}}\n\n{{Coord|43|22|44|N|80|42|39|W|region:CA_type:city|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communities in Waterloo Region, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Wilmot, Ontario]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = New Hamburg\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Unincorporated community\n|motto                  = \n|image_skyline          = Newhamburg ON tac.jpg\n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = Peel Street in New Hamburg\n|image_flag             = \n|flag_size              = \n|image_seal             = \n|seal_size              = \n|image_shield           = \n|shield_size            = \n|city_logo              = \n|citylogo_size          = \n|image_map              = \n|mapsize                = \n|map_caption            = \n|image_map1             = \n|mapsize1               = \n|map_caption1           = \n|pushpin_map            = <!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|pushpin_mapsize        = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Canada]]\n|subdivision_type1      = Province\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Ontario]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Regional municipality]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo|Waterloo]]\n|subdivision_type3      = Township\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Wilmot, Ontario|Wilmot]]\n|established_title2     = 1854\n|timezone               = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|utc_offset             = -5\n|timezone_DST           = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST         = -4\n|coordinates            = {{coord|43|22|44|N|80|42|39|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_ft           = \n|postal_code_type       = [[Canadian postal code#Forward sortation areas|Forward sortation area]]\n|postal_code            = [[List of N postal codes of Canada|N3A]]\n|area_code              = [[Area codes 519 and 226|519 and 226]]\n|blank_name             = [[National Topographic System|NTS]] Map\n|blank_info             = 040P07\n|blank1_name            = [[Geographical Names Board of Canada|GNBC]] Code\n|blank1_info            = FEBVH\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n\n'''New Hamburg''' is a community of approximately 7,930 (2011 stats) in [[Wilmot, Ontario|Wilmot Township]].  Founded in 1854 it is a rural township of the [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo, Ontario]]. It is bordered by [[Baden, Ontario|Baden]] to the east and [[Perth County, Ontario|Perth County]] to the west, and close to the cities of [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]], [[Waterloo, Ontario|Waterloo]] and [[Stratford, Ontario|Stratford]].\n\nThe [[Nith River]] winds through town and flows through the downtown core, which is home to a 50-foot [[Water wheel|waterwheel]] built in 1990.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Miller Cressman |fir